, England","Mickleton, Gloucestershire, England":"Mickleton, Gloucestershire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1459–1560":"1459–1560","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","1474–1515":"1474–1515","1508–1538":"1508–1538","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1505–1558":"1505–1558","1459":"1459","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1474":"1474","1560":"1560","1508":"1508","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Ashleworth, Gloucestershire, England":"Ashleworth, Gloucestershire, England","Mickleton, Gloucestershire, England":"Mickleton, Gloucestershire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gifford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Eleanor Gifford was born in 1459, in England, United Kingdom. She married William Porter in 1480, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1560, in her hometown, at the age of 101."},"et":{"1459–1560":"1459–1560","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1474–1515":"1474–1515","1508–1538":"1508–1538","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1505–1558":"1505–1558","1459":"1459","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1474":"1474","1560":"1560","1508":"1508","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1505":"1505","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ashleworth, Gloucestershire, England":"Ashleworth, Gloucestershire, England","Mickleton, Gloucestershire, England":"Mickleton, Gloucestershire, England","Eng